o validate\n        \n    Returns:\n        bool: True if the date is valid, False otherwise\n    """\n    # Check if input is empty\n    if not date or not isinstance(date, str):\n        return False\n    \n    # Check pattern: must have exactly two \'-\' separators\n    parts = date.split(\'-\')\n    if len(parts) != 3:\n        return False\n    \n    day_str, month_str, year_str = parts\n    \n    # Check if all parts are numeric\n    if not (day_str.isdigit() and month_str.isdigit() and year_str.isdigit()):\n        return False\n    \n    # Convert to integers\n    try:\n        day = int(day_str)\n        month = int(month_str)\n        year = int(year_str)\n    except ValueError:\n        return False\n    \n    # Check month range (1-12)\n    if month < 1 or month > 12:\n        return False\n    \n    # Check day range based on month\n    if month in [1, 3, 5, 7, 8, 10, 12]:\n        max_days = 31\n    elif month in [4, 6, 9, 11]:\n        max_days = 30\n    elif month == 2:\n        # Simple leap year check (divisible by 4)\n        max_days = 29 if year % 4 == 0 else 28\n    else:\n        return False\n    \n    # Check day is within valid range\n    if day < 1 or day > max_days:\n        return False\n    \n    return True'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': 'I notice that the implementation I created doesn\'t match the expected behavior from the examples provided. Looking at the examples, it seems like the function should validate pattern-based strings rather than actual calendar dates. The examples show that \'aa-bb-cccc\' returns True and \'xx-yy-zzzz\' returns False, suggesting this is about pattern validation rather than actual date validation. Let me read the current file and then rewrite it with the correct implementation.\n\n```json\n[\n    {\n        "command_name": "Editor.read",\n        "args": {\n            "path": "/Users/stream/TheAgentTester2/MetaGPT/workspace/date_validator.py"\n        }\n    }\n]\n```'}, {'role': 'user', 'content':